        "text": "An attempt to articulate just how vast and magnificent the scope of Akira Kurosawaâs ä¹± (Ran) is will inevitably fall short. Recognized as a master of epics, including his ä¸äººã®ä¾ (Seven Samurai, 1954), Kurosawa reimagines Shakespeareâs tragic King Lear set in medieval Japan. Each shot is labored and precise, as sublime landscapes overwhelm the screen, dwarfing the armies of men fighting below.Â\n\nAt the center of the ensuing wars is Hidetora Ichimonji, an aging warlord. Ichimonji divides his conquered land between his three sons, Taro, Jiro, Saburo. The Ichimonji clan, however, will not settle for less than everything. Father and sons scheme against one another, leading to violent plots for control over the kingdom. Greed poisons the Ichimonjiâs bloodline, pervasive and all-consuming. The tragedy that unfolds is indeed as poignant as any great Shakespeare work.Â\n\nThe road ahead is lined with bodies, blood, jealousy, paranoiaâand itâs a long way to the bottom from the throne. Kurosawa, confronting his own mortality and legacy, achieves a titanic masterpiece with Ran. Few films so deeply grasp the tragedy of war at this visceral level. While Ran is not an easy watch, itâs a must-watch for all."
